\f0\b\fs24 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Pop-II
\f1\b0  is tthe 
\f0\b older, lower-mass, metal-poor stellar populations
\f1\b0  that provide an entirely separate calibrator block in the H0DN network. The category is doing real work in the H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f1  debate, so it's worth a careful walk through.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 The Population I/II/III taxonomy\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 The original Pop-I/II distinction comes from 
\f0\b Walter Baade in 1944
\f1\b0 . Looking at M31 and its companions during the wartime blackout of Mt. Wilson (which dramatically improved seeing on the city-side), Baade was the first to clearly resolve two stellar populations:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Population I
\f1\b0 : young, metal-rich, dust-and-gas-rich, found in spiral arms \'97 
\f3\i blue
\f1\i0  in CMDs because populated up to high luminosity by hot main-sequence stars.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Population II
\f1\b0 : old, metal-poor, gas-poor, found in halos and globular clusters \'97 
\f3\i red
\f1\i0  in CMDs because main sequence has burned down to the turnoff at modest luminosity, and the dominant bright stars are red giants.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 (Pop III, hypothetical first-generation zero-metallicity stars, exists in theory but has never been definitively observed and isn't relevant for distance work.)\
Modern stellar evolution understanding refines this into a continuum \'97 there's no sharp Pop-I/II divide; populations are characterized by age and metallicity along a continuous spectrum, with old metal-poor populations having different observable distance-indicator properties from young metal-rich ones. But the labels remain useful as shorthand for "the kinds of stars that live in halos and old populations" vs "the kinds of stars that live in star-forming disks."\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

