\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 ~0.2\'961 day periods, NIR PLR\cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 (Used for MW/dwarf, not extragalactic SN Ia ladders)\cell \lastrow\row
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 All four share a common physical origin: they are 
\f0\b late evolutionary phases of low-mass (~0.8\'962 M
\f4 \'a8\'91
\f0 ) stars
\f1\b0  with main-sequence ages of several Gyr. This puts them in the "old population" bucket regardless of where they actually live in any given galaxy (which can be halo, disk, or bulge \'97 old stars are everywhere old populations are).\
The cosmologically relevant Pop-II indicators on the figure are TRGB, JAGB, and Mira; RR Lyrae are essential for MW/Local Group calibration but are too faint to detect in distant SN Ia hosts and don't contribute directly to the third rung.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Why "Pop-II" is the relevant category for H
\f5 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  work\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 The category exists in the H0DN framework not because of stellar physics per se, but because of a pragmatic argument about 
\f0\b systematics independence
\f1\b0 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Pop-I tracers
\f1\b0  (Cepheids, SNe II) live in:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Star-forming disks of late-type spirals\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Crowded inner regions\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Dusty, metal-rich environments\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Galaxies of recent or ongoing star formation\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Pop-II tracers
\f1\b0  (TRGB, JAGB, Mira) live in:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Halos and outer disks of any galaxy type\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Uncrowded, smooth-profile regions\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Lower-dust environments\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Galaxies of any morphological type, including E/S0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The 
\f0\b systematic concerns are largely orthogonal
\f1\b0 :\

