\cf0 The striking pattern: 
\f0\b Pop-II values span 67.8 to 73.8 \'97 a much larger range than Pop-I values
\f1\b0 . This is more than just "noise"; it tells you that Pop-II calibrator pipelines have substantial methodological dispersion that Pop-I (Cepheid) pipelines don't.\
This is the key empirical observation that makes the H0DN framework necessary. In a world where TRGB-vs-CCHP disagreement was just statistical, you could pick one and move on. In the world we actually live in, multiple competent analyses of the same TRGB physics give H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f1  values ranging from 70 to 74, and you have to ask which methodological choice is right \'97 or marginalize over them.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 What the Pop-II combined picture says\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 The H0DN combined Pop-II value sits around 
\f0\b 72 \'b1 1.5
\f1\b0 , somewhere between CCHP at the bottom and the TRGB+SBF route at the top. It's lower than SH0ES (73.04 \'b1 1.04) by about 1 km/s/Mpc, and higher than Planck (67.4 \'b1 0.5) by about 4.5 km/s/Mpc.\
A few observations:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 1. Pop-II prefers a high H
\f5 \uc0\u8320 
\f0 , but not as decisively as Pop-I.
\f1\b0  Combined Pop-II is in ~3\uc0\u963  tension with Planck \'97 meaningful but not the 5\u963  that Pop-I gives. The reduced significance comes mostly from the larger error bars (~2\'d7 Pop-I) and from CCHP pulling slightly low.\

\f0\b 2. The Pop-II measurements that go through SBF (Jensen+25, the highest-precision Pop-II measurement) sit near SH0ES.
\f1\b0  This is non-trivial: it means the pure TRGB
\f6 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 SN Ia route (CCHP) and the TRGB
\f6 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 SBF
\f6 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 SN Ia route (Jensen+25) disagree by ~3.4 km/s/Mpc despite using essentially the same TRGB anchoring. The disagreement is at the SBF rung and the SN Ia rung, not at the TRGB rung itself.\

\f0\b 3. JAGB is the wild card.
\f1\b0  Freedman+25's JWST-only JAGB value is 67.8, indistinguishable from Planck. Lee+24's JAGB analysis with similar data gives 73.3. This is a 5.5 km/s/Mpc spread on a single physical method, and resolving which is right is one of the most active areas of current Pop-II work. The resolution will likely come from ngVLA-era and Roman-era Pop-II observations with much larger samples; it's not going to be settled in the next 1\'962 years.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Why Pop-II is hard\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 The Pop-II calibrator rung has some genuine difficulties that don't apply to Cepheids:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 1. Tip-detection is fundamentally a discontinuity-finding problem in noisy data.
\f1\b0 \
The TRGB is the 
\f3\i tip
\f1\i0  of the red giant branch \'97 i.e., the maximum luminosity reached by RGB stars before the helium flash. In a CMD, this appears as an edge in the luminosity function: stars are present below the tip, sharply absent above it. Detecting an edge in noisy, finite-statistics data requires choices about smoothing kernel, edge-detection algorithm, color cut, magnitude binning. Different choices give different tips by ~0.04 mag, propagating to ~0.5 km/s/Mpc in H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f1 .\
This is unlike Cepheid PLR fitting, which is a regression problem with well-understood statistical properties. TRGB tip-finding is genuinely an algorithmic choice, and the choice matters at the precision level we're discussing.\

\f0\b 2. The metallicity sensitivity is real, just smaller.
\f1\b0 \
The I-band TRGB tip magnitude is famously 
\f3\i insensitive
\f1\i0  to metallicity for [Fe/H] > -1.5 \'97 but it's not zero-sensitive, and the residual dependence (~0.02 mag/dex slope) accumulates when you go from MW globular cluster calibration ([Fe/H] ~ -1) to LMC ([Fe/H] ~ -0.4) to NGC 4258 ([Fe/H] ~ +0.2) and to SN Ia hosts (typically [Fe/H] ~ 0).\
JAGB has a stronger metallicity dependence that's been the subject of substantial recent work; the Freedman+25 vs Lee+24 disagreement on JAGB H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f1  is partly traceable to different metallicity treatments.\

\f0\b 3. The third rung is harder.
\f1\b0 \
For Cepheids, the third rung is "calibrated SN Ia 
\f6 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  Hubble-flow SN Ia" \'97 you have ~280 Hubble-flow SN Ia and the bridge is well-established. For Pop-II via SBF or FP, you have a 
\f3\i second
\f1\i0  third-rung calibration step (TRGB 
\f6 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  SBF 
\f6 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  Hubble flow), which adds a layer of systematic propagation.\

\f0\b 4. JWST is rewriting the picture in real time.
\f1\b0 \
JWST has only been operating since mid-2022, and the Pop-II measurements that depend on JWST data (Freedman+25, Anand+24b, Jensen+25, Lee+24) are all ~1\'962 years old. The systematic understanding of JWST photometry is maturing rapidly. Some of the spread in current Pop-II H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f1  values is plausibly transient \'97 it'll narrow as JWST calibration becomes better characterized.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

